There are broadly two ways that I can make money from sponsorships:=C2=A0
Cost Per Impression (CPM): A company pays me to get its message in front of=
 this group of smart, curious people based on how many people read it, and =
regardless of whether anyone clicks the button to learn more or sign up or =
buy. Most of the sponsorships will be CPM.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Cost Per Acquisition (CPA): A company pays me a certain amount for each per=
son who signs up, subscribes to, or buys its product. For example, if I did=
 a deal with Fictional Shirt Company at $100 CPA, and 90 of you bought shir=
ts after clicking my link, Fictional Shirt Company would pay me $9,000. I=
=E2=80=99ll do these less often.=C2=A0
Typically, CPM deals make more sense because there=E2=80=99s value to a com=
pany in getting in front of you even if you don=E2=80=99t buy immediately. =
There=E2=80=99s an idea in marketing that someone needs to see a product se=
ven times before buying, and while the number might not be exactly seven, i=
t=E2=80=99s rarely one.=20
I=E2=80=99m certainly not going to put on a hard enough sell to bring that =
number down. I=E2=80=99d rather just expose you to products and companies I=
 like (and often use myself), and if you=E2=80=99re interested, great!=C2=
=A0I have much more to lose than gain by hawking bad products.
Sometimes, though, CPA deals just make sense.=C2=A0
