Do Not Pay is one of my favorite companies that I=E2=80=99ve discovered in =
the past year. Joshua Browder, a 23-year-old Stanford graduate and the son =
of Red Notice author Bill Browder, founded the company when he was 17 to he=
lp people in the UK get out of parking tickets.
Now, the company has expanded to the US, and handles everything from parkin=
g tickets to suing people and companies in small claims court. Last summer,=
 it launched a virtual credit card that subscribers can enter when they=E2=
=80=99re signing up for free trials so that they=E2=80=99re not auto-charge=
d when the trial expires.
Just last week, they launched a new product that allows subscribers to clai=
m their unemployment payments at the press of a button. Filing for unemploy=
ment has been a nightmare for many. They desperately need the money, but th=
ey aren=E2=80=99t able to figure out the forms, the websites are overloaded=
, and they can=E2=80=99t get through when they try to call in. DoNotPay wil=
l handle all of that. It guides them through the claim form via a chat inte=
rface, submits the form for them, and in states that require a phone call, =
calls the unemployment office every hour until it gets through. Once benefi=
ts are approved, it also automatically handles the weekly certifications of=
 unemployment necessary to keep receiving checks. It makes a painful proces=
s easy.
DoNotPay is so magical because it uses software to help people do all of th=
e things that they should be doing but don=E2=80=99t because they don=E2=80=
=99t know how, they forget, or it=E2=80=99s too much of a pain in the ass. =
The more capabilities that DoNotPay adds, the more ludicrously cheap its $3=
/mo subscription seems. It works, because after all of the painful work of =
onboarding new capabilities and translating them to software, DoNotPay has =
almost zero marginal costs.
